My Review:
I fell to plotting ways of short-circuiting the machine. Perhaps if I shifted my body about so that the two nodes would come together — No, not only was there no room but it might electrocute me. I shuddered. Whoever else I was, I was no Samson. I had no desire to destroy myself even if it destroyed the machine; I wanted freedom, not destruction. It was exhausting, for no matter what the scheme I conceived, there was one constant flaw –myself. There was no getting around it. I could no more escape than I could think of my identity. Perhaps, I thought, the two things are involved with each other. When I discover who I am, I’ll be free.

this book was everything. kafkaesque, coming-of-age, existential, absurd, surreal… i’ve never read anything like this before. i could read it everyday for the rest of my life and still pick up something new. i’m supremely jealous of anyone who read this in a high school. SHOULDVE bEEN ME. idgaf ab gatsby or whatever else, THIS is REQUIRED reading, THE GReaT AMERICAN NOVEL!!! the chapters are connected but could also pass for individual short story--the narrative has such a dream-like quality it's unbelievable. this would’ve been a 5-star read but the last 130 pages felt very heavy-handed. or maybe I lost the plot after reading this one for over a month..

Title: The Sirens of Titan
Author: Kurt Vonnegut Jr.
Bookshelves: war, i-cried, better-than-expected, recommended-to-me, dark, has-vision, shocking, mentally-ill
Bookshelves with positions: war (#8), i-cried (#19), better-than-expected (#43), recommended-to-me (#19), dark (#36), has-vision (#30), shocking (#7), mentally-ill (#3)
My Review:
dear a,

next time you narrate an entire novel word for word, please don’t hold me at gunpoint and have me swear on my life that it would be the next book i read. i was counting on my amnesia to kick in because half of the time i barely retain a sentence when you do this. unfortunately for me, this book is just so crazy that even when you summarized it, i remembered it all.

it took me a while to forgive you for spoiling the fate of unk’s friend. HOW could you TELL ME and then FORCE ME TO READ IT??!?! but even vonnegut gives it up, and doesn’t hesitate to remind us every time he can. he could have revealed it later, and it would’ve been gut-wrenching, but vonny is not for the useless dramatics, he keeps it real. and this is what it is about, really. everything is hopeless, but i’m too bewildered to properly wrap my head around the scope of the horror. who has time to shed a tear? this is war, mercury is next on the itinerary, time to jump ship.

at the last chapter on titan, i have to admit i started panicking. suddenly i felt very very anxious and scared. it is dangerous to live even one day. you tell yourself there must be at least some things in your control, only to find out that the causes of things are so far removed from anything human. instead, they are traced back to the hypnotic anarchy of a distant planet. and here i thought i was past the age for an existential crisis.

i'm not too fond of dark comedies or anyone who claims to shed light on “human nature”. usually, it feels like they are trying to sell me a story full of gimmicks with a forced cheeky attitude. but vonnegut isn’t trying to do anything but tell his story, and it is all effortless. he is ironic and imaginative and the writing is simple. he is comfortable in his voice and has nothing to prove. i wish i could shake his hand.

i have mixed feelings; i dunno if i should give this one 3 or 5 stars. i hear this isn’t even the best vonnegut, and i suppose once this gloominess subsides i will be more excited about the fact that i have the chance to read the rest of his works. totally can’t wait... i have more to say, so when you have proper wifi, please call me <3

Title: Liar & Spy
Author: Rebecca Stead
My Review: i have lots of love for middle-grade books and short stories. when done well, it’s always fascinating to see developed characters and plot lines written with just a few pages and simple language. reading stead’s novel as an adult, her style feels almost formulaic and too perfect—she’s got the craft down—but it’s still touching. if stead has one fan in the world, it’s me. even though her books are for eleven-year-olds, she never talks down to the reader, which i appreciate because some of these authors don’t respect their readers’ intelligence. and she isn’t afraid to explore complex themes. it’s really fun cuz why is she lowk giving marxist but ofc i would’ve never picked that up in the second grade. there’s something for all ages to enjoy in her writing. and well, i could go on. this book is all of that but it was also a little boring to me…i just wasn’t as moved with this one. it’s a real bummer because i think her other book is amazing. but this was cute. i was tearing up. it is so hard being thirteen.
Private Notes: i also like how the meaning of the title swapped part way through. at first i thought the mc was the liar ( lying to his dad) and safer was the spy. but when we found out that safer was lying about mr.x, he becomes the liar and mc is the spy cuz he was the only one taking it seriously the entire time.

Title: Cannery Row (Cannery Row, #1)
Author: John Steinbeck
My Review:
for the past couple of summers, i get this penguin drop caps edition of cannery row from the library, hoping to read it before school begins. it has an ocean blue cover and the edges of the pages are also painted with the same gorgeous color. isn’t it just so fun when books do that? it really is quite striking, which is why i couldn’t help bringing it home every summer even if i never get past the first page. this time i took a nap after each chapter i read. this made it more bearable..

i’m a big fan of bold, dramatic, imaginative use of language. even if a book doesn’t do it for me plot wise, if the author can write a mean sentence, i cant help but respect them for their craft. steinbeck’s prose leaves much to be desired. he’ll describe a lake or the sky at dusk, which are all very pretty things, but when he is describing them it doesn’t SOUND pretty. IT DOESNT SOUND LIKE ANYTHING. there’s no feeling. i really have to use my imagination to enhance his vision and try not to fall asleep because he is giving us the bare bones. this gets really tiring since every chapter extensively describes a car or the layout of a room which is already superfluous given that most of these chapters are LESS THAN FIVE PAGES LONG. i can see this working for other people, but i need the prose to be livelier. this is a story of a small town and hopeful people trying to make the best of what they can, but the writing is not doing anything to create this atmosphere. (imo. sorry Steinbeck stans..)

i dunno if i got used to his style or if i started gaslighting myself, because suddenly i was hooked. i’ll be struggling to keep my eyes open and then the next moment i’m laughing out loud (rare; i’m a very serious person) and then i have to catch myself because oh my gosh this boring old book made me laugh. some parts are so soft and introspective they leave a lump in my throat. and steinbeck is surprisingly snarky when he wants to be. for a book so tiny—and accounting for the first half where i was barely awake, making my sample size even smaller—steinbeck explores a vast range of emotions and human experiences in so little pages.

cannery row reads like a collection of sketches that have yet to be completed. every other chapter could technically be read as a standalone, and in these chapters characters are introduced and never explicitly mentioned again. cuz of this a lot of the characters that interested me are never explored after their one and only chapter. even the main characters are not fleshed out in a way that appeals to me. it was still fun, but i wanted more. for this reason, i give it a solid 3 stars x
